Currently SharpDX resources are only disposed if dispose is called explicitly. When this doesn't happen, they will not be disposed, resulting in memory leak.

See:
https://github.com/sharpdx/SharpDX/issues/240

Instead of this:

``` C#
        protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
        {
                if (disposing)
                {
                    SharpDX.Utilities.Dispose(ref something);
                }
        }
```

this should be used:

``` C#
        protected override void Dispose(bool disposing)
        {
                SharpDX.Utilities.Dispose(ref something);
        }
```

I don't know if this has already been reported. It's a problem that exists in the default XNA game, so I have a hard time believing I'm the first to notice.

If Game.Exit() is called within Game.Update() -- say when the Back button is pressed -- the Game.Tick() continues with the Game.DoDraw() call, throwing a MonoGameGLException in BlendState.ApplyState().

GL.GetError() returned InvalidFramebufferOperationExt

I propose changing this ...

```
    public void Exit()
    {
        Platform.Exit();
    }
```

... to this ...

```
    public void Exit()
    {
        Platform.Exit();
        _suppressDraw = true;
    }
```

Let me know if it's something that remains to be addressed and I'll create a branch and PR tomorrow.
